Task 1: Generate SSH Key Pair
Objective: Create a secure SSH key pair (public/private) for authentication.
Subtask 1.1: Check for Existing SSH Keys
Open a terminal on your local machine.
Run the following command to check for existing keys:
ls ~/.ssh/
If you see files like id_rsa and id_rsa.pub, you may skip key generation (or create a new pair).
If the .ssh directory doesn’t exist, proceed to Subtask 1.2.
Subtask 1.2: Generate a New Key Pair
Run the following command (replace your_email@example.com with your email):

ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"
-t rsa: Specifies the key type (RSA).
-b 4096: Sets key length to 4096 bits (secure default).
-C: Adds a comment (optional).
Follow the prompts:

Press Enter to save the key in the default location (~/.ssh/id_rsa).
Enter a passphrase (recommended for security) or leave empty.
Verify the generated keys:

ls ~/.ssh/
Expected output: id_rsa (private key) and id_rsa.pub (public key).
Troubleshooting Tips
If ssh-keygen is not found, install OpenSSH:
sudo apt install openssh-client  # Debian/Ubuntu
sudo yum install openssh-clients # CentOS/RHEL
Task 2: Configure SSH Server on the Remote Machine
Objective: Set up the remote Linux system to accept SSH key-based authentication.
Subtask 2.1: Install SSH Server (if not present)
Log in to the remote machine (via console or existing SSH).

Install the SSH server (if not installed):

sudo apt install openssh-server  # Debian/Ubuntu
sudo yum install openssh-server  # CentOS/RHEL
Start and enable the SSH service:

sudo systemctl start sshd
sudo systemctl enable sshd
Subtask 2.2: Copy Public Key to Remote Machine
On your local machine, copy the public key to the remote server:

ssh-copy-id username@remote_server_ip
Replace username and remote_server_ip with actual values.
Enter the remote system’s password when prompted.
Alternatively, manually append the public key:

cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub | ssh username@remote_server_ip "mkdir -p ~/.ssh && cat >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys"
Subtask 2.3: Secure SSH Server Configuration
Edit the SSH server config file on the remote machine:
sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config
Update the following settings for security:
PasswordAuthentication no         # Disable password login
PermitRootLogin no                # Disable root login
PubkeyAuthentication yes          # Enable key-based auth
Restart the SSH service:
sudo systemctl restart sshd
Troubleshooting Tips
If ssh-copy-id fails, ensure the remote server allows password authentication temporarily.
Check firewall rules (sudo ufw allow 22 for Ubuntu).
Task 3: Log in Remotely Using SSH
Objective: Establish a secure SSH connection using key-based authentication.
Subtask 3.1: Test SSH Login
From your local machine, run:
ssh username@remote_server_ip
If a passphrase was set, enter it.
Expected outcome: You should log in without a password prompt.
Subtask 3.2: Verify Connection
Check your remote session:
whoami  # Should return your remote username
hostname  # Should return the remote system's hostname
Troubleshooting Tips
If login fails, verify:
The public key is in ~/.ssh/authorized_keys on the remote machine.
Permissions: chmod 700 ~/.ssh and chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys.
